# Winning Hack-Nation Challenge 03: a deep research playbook

**Build a calibrated, IPHS-validated facility intelligence system on Databricks Free Edition — and avoid the four invisible cliffs that will eat your weekend.** This report consolidates ~14,000 words of underlying research into actionable findings across ten domains: prior winners, the Databricks 2026 stack, agentic IDP state-of-the-art, Indian healthcare data sources, IPHS/SARA validator rules, the Cursor 3.x ecosystem, Lovable→Vercel integration, demo craft, creative angles, and risks. The four cliffs you must internalize before writing a line of code: **(1) Knowledge Assistant and Supervisor Agent are not available on Databricks Free Edition** — your "agent" must be a custom `ResponsesAgent`; **(2) Databricks Apps require Premium tier**, so your FastAPI lives on Vercel, not in-platform; **(3) Free Edition compute has a restricted outbound-internet allowlist**, meaning every external tool call (HFR lookup, web scrape, OCR API) must be proxied through the Vercel layer or precomputed into Unity Catalog; **(4) Vercel→Databricks browser calls fail CORS** unconditionally. Architecting around these four constraints from hour zero is worth more than any feature you could otherwise build.

The judging rubric — Discovery & Verification 35%, IDP Innovation 30%, Social Impact 25%, UX 10% — rewards a specific shape of project: a calibrated extraction pipeline with statistical guarantees, a rule-grounded validator agent, a geospatial impact narrative, and exactly enough UX to make those facts feel real. Build to that shape.

## 1. What Hack-Nation winners actually look like

The public Hack-Nation winner archive at projects.hack-nation.ai is a JavaScript SPA that does not render to scrapers, so direct evidence is sparse. The single best-documented 2025 winner is the **Boston-hub OpenAI-track first prize: an "Email Communication Graph"** by Karlo Vrancic, Marc and Alec — a deployed full-stack system that constructs a corporate communication graph from email and runs graph-theoretic analysis, **pitched as "automating what costs six figures in consulting"**. The team shipped a working frontend + backend in ~18 hours, leaned hard into the sponsor's API surface, and used a quantified-replacement framing rather than a capability framing.

Adjacent evidence — Databricks' own GenAI hackathon winners (HEB "Shop is Easy", Yahoo Finance, GreenLight Biosciences "AdaptiveFilters" with Mosaic AI Model Serving + Vector Search), MIT Hacking Medicine's 2025 "HospiTwin" ED digital twin, Microsoft's 2025 RiskWise overall winner, and Out-of-Pocket SF's "U good?" patient-navigator that **autonomously navigated insurance phone IVRs** — converges tightly on five recurring traits.

**Top-tier submissions consistently demonstrate deep sponsor-stack use** (not LangChain wrapping a Databricks logo), **a quantified human-cost replacement** ("replaces six figures of consulting" / "ED boarding kills X patients"), **a deployed clickable frontend** (judges play your demo before reading anything else), **one real downstream action** rather than pure chat (book the appointment, dispatch the SMS, fill the referral), and **engineering-maturity tells** like Unity Catalog governance, MLflow tracing, and explicit failure-mode disclosure. Databricks' own Solutions Architect guide is unusually direct: *"pre-test 1–2 impressive questions and include them in your demo. It's a guaranteed way to score extra points."* Take that literally.

The opposite pattern — bottom tier — is a notebook-only project with mock data, generic problem framing ("improving healthcare"), all-engineer presenter team, and a chat interface that doesn't actually do anything in the world.

## 2. The April 2026 Databricks stack, navigated from Free Edition

Agent Bricks went GA on **April 14, 2026** as a governed enterprise agent platform. Document Intelligence, Custom Agents on Apps, Knowledge Assistant, and Multi-Agent Supervisor are all GA on paid plans, and the Foundation Model API exposes Claude Sonnet 4.6, Sonnet 4.5, GPT-5.4 family, Gemini 3.1 Pro, Llama 3.3-70B, gpt-oss-120B, plus the embedding models `databricks-gte-large-en` (1024d, 8K window — your default) and Qwen3-Embedding-0.6B (multilingual, 32K window — strongly consider for Hindi/Urdu records). But on Free Edition, the picture is materially narrower.

**Knowledge Assistant and Multi-Agent Supervisor are explicitly unsupported on Free Edition.** Build with the **`ResponsesAgent` MLflow interface** in a single notebook, optionally orchestrating with LangGraph or PydanticAI underneath. Vector Search is capped at **one endpoint and one Vector Search Unit** (2M vectors at 768d — you'll use under 1% for 10k records), Direct Vector Access is unsupported so your index must be a **Delta Sync Index off a Delta table with Change Data Feed enabled**, and you must use Databricks-hosted embedding endpoints (a community thread documents 5K external-embedding chunks taking over an hour vs. minutes on the managed endpoint). Set **`query_type="HYBRID"`** at query time — for a dataset with messy facility names, addresses, and PIN codes, BM25 + dense fusion is non-negotiable for clinical-grade recall.

**MLflow 3 Tracing is the second pillar of the IDP-Innovation score.** As of MLflow 3.3.x in April 2026, tracing is fully OpenTelemetry-compatible with GenAI semantic conventions for `RETRIEVER`, `TOOL`, `LLM`, `CHAIN`, `AGENT`, and `PARSER` span types. Three instrumentation patterns combine in one trace: the **`@mlflow.trace(span_type=...)`** decorator (parent/child inferred from the call stack), **per-framework autologging** (`mlflow.openai.autolog()`, `mlflow.anthropic.autolog()`, `mlflow.langchain.autolog()`), and **manual `mlflow.start_span()`** context managers for fine-grained sub-steps. Critically, on serverless Free Edition compute autolog is **not on by default** — call it explicitly at the top of the notebook. Token and cost accounting are auto-captured via `mlflow.chat.tokenUsage`. As of January 2026 you can write traces directly to **Unity Catalog Delta tables** queryable from Databricks SQL — this is the foundation of your row-level + step-level citation story.

**Genie comes in two flavors that share a name.** Genie Spaces is the natural-language-to-SQL product (20 questions/min via UI, 5/min via the API; max 30 tables per space). Genie Code (formerly Databricks Assistant) is the in-notebook coding assistant with chat and agent modes. The hackathon's highest-impact trick is to **wrap your `facilities` Delta table in a single Genie Space**, add `COMMENT ON COLUMN` annotations and ≥5 example queries, and **expose Genie as a tool inside your agent** via the Conversation API or a UC function. Without the comments and examples Genie hallucinates SQL; spend fifteen minutes on this and it becomes magical.

**Free Edition's other hard constraints worth pinning to a wall:** serverless-only compute with no GPUs, **outbound internet restricted to a trusted-domain allowlist** (your agent cannot pip-install or curl arbitrary endpoints from a notebook), **one workspace per account with no shared metastore** (each teammate signs up individually and you sync via Git Repos), one SQL warehouse maxed at 2X-Small, **CORS is not configurable on serving endpoints** (you must proxy through Vercel), and **payload limits of 4MB request, 1MB log, 297-second execution**. There is no documented Databricks block on Pakistan, but VPN-mediated email-OTP signups occasionally hang — register from a stable network first via Google sign-in, then VPN. Pick a US workspace region (us-east-2 or us-west-2) for maximum feature support.

The recommended hackathon layout is a single notebook implementing the agent with `ResponsesAgent`, a UC managed volume `hackathon.bronze.raw_files` for the VF Excel, four schemas (`bronze`/`silver`/`gold`/`ai`), a Delta Sync Vector Search index on the gold facilities table, a registered UC model deployed to a Model Serving endpoint, and **one canonical "ops" workspace** (not all teammates' workspaces) used as the demo environment. Skip Lakeflow Declarative Pipelines — the boilerplate cost outweighs the benefit at 10K rows.

## 3. Agentic IDP that wins the 30% innovation pillar

The 2025–2026 SOTA for medical text extraction has converged on a **three-layer pattern: Pydantic-first schema definition, structured/constrained decoding, and agentic orchestration with retries**. Instructor (567-labs, ~3M monthly downloads) is the de facto Pydantic→LLM bridge; PydanticAI is the Pydantic team's official agent runtime with typed tools, durable execution, and Pydantic Graph. Both wrap native function-calling and add Tenacity retries on `ValidationError`. The "Let Me Speak Freely?" paper (EMNLP Industry 2024) shows rigid JSON constraints can hurt reasoning, so the canonical hybrid pattern is to **include a free-form `reasoning` and `evidence_quote` field inside your typed Pydantic model** — a scratchpad without sacrificing validation.

For the multi-pass loop, four techniques have aged best in the literature: **Self-Consistency** (Wang et al., ICLR 2023, +5–15pp F1 on long-tail extraction fields), **Reflexion** (Shinn et al., NeurIPS 2023, the canonical Actor/Evaluator/Self-Reflection trio), **CRITIC** (Gou et al., ICLR 2024, tool-augmented self-critique — maps perfectly onto a Validator-Agent that calls IPHS rule lookups), and **Self-Refine** (Madaan et al., NeurIPS 2023, +5–20% across most generation tasks). Naive **LLM-as-judge has been shown to hit only 9.3% recall on hallucination detection in clinical text** (arXiv:2604.06216) — always pair it with a structured rubric and decomposed sub-questions. For agentic medical work, MedAgentBench (NEJM AI 2025) shows Claude 3.5 Sonnet v2 hitting 69.67% on EHR agentic tasks zero-shot — **no fine-tuning needed for hackathon-quality results**.

The **confidence and prediction interval section is where the IDP-Innovation 30% lives**, because the challenge prompt explicitly asks for statistical methods. Three techniques are right-sized for a 24–48 hour build, ranked by impact-to-effort:

**Rank 1 (must-build, 2–4 hours): self-consistency disagreement.** Sample N=5 extractions per facility per field at temperature 0.7; compute the per-field agreement rate as the confidence score. Black-box, works on any provider, gives you a real number for the UI badge, and beats verbalized confidence which is documented broken (Tian et al. EMNLP 2023, Xiong et al. ICLR 2024 — average ECE >0.377 for GPT-3/3.5/Vicuna; GPT-4 AUROC ~62.7%, barely above chance).

**Rank 2 (defining moat, 4–8 hours): split conformal prediction.** Hand-label a 200-record gold set, use the agreement rate from Rank 1 as the nonconformity score, and emit **finite-sample 90% prediction sets per field** with formal coverage guarantees. The textbook reference is Shrestha & Kim's "Conformal Prediction for Risk-Controlled Medical Entity Extraction" (arXiv:2603.00924), which reports needing τ up to 0.99 on free-text radiology to hit α=0.10 FDR — directly relevant to noisy Indian facility notes. Use the `mapie` library or roll a 50-line implementation. **This single technique answers the challenge's "statistical prediction intervals" requirement and is your strongest defense in the rubric.**

**Rank 3 (cheap second signal, 2–3 hours): token-logprob-weighted span confidence.** Sum logprobs of the extracted span / span length, normalize via Platt scaling on the same calibration set, combine with Rank 1 via weighted sum. **Skip semantic entropy** (Farquhar et al. *Nature* 2024, 10× cost), **skip Semantic Entropy Probes** (need hidden-state access), **skip naive verbalized confidence**.

For hallucination detection, the cheapest, highest-recall pattern is **substring grounding**: every extracted value carries an `evidence_span: str` and `evidence_char_offset: tuple[int,int]`, validated via fuzzy substring match (rapidfuzz ratio ≥0.95). This catches roughly 80% of fabrication for free. Pair with SelfCheckGPT-NLI on narrative fields ("advanced surgery available" vs. raw notes) for the remaining tail. Both feed naturally into the Trust Scorer.

## 4. Indian healthcare data: pick ABDM HFR, back-stop with data.gov.in

Of the three candidates, **ABDM's Health Facility Registry is the strongest primary cross-validation source, with data.gov.in's NHP Hospital Directory as a deterministic safety net**. Here is the comparative reality:

| Source | Records | Bulk download | API | Lat/lon | Field overlap with VF | Hackathon effort |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| NRHM HMIS | ~200K reporting | No | None public | No | Low (operational KPIs only) | 20–30h, high risk |
| **ABDM HFR** | **~419K (Aug 2025)** | No | OAuth sandbox | **Yes** | **Very high** | 16–24h, medium risk |
| data.gov.in NHP | ~3,000 | **Yes (CSV/JSON)** | Yes (api.data.gov.in) | Yes | High | **6–10h, low risk** |

HMIS is service-delivery KPIs, not a directory — facility-level rows are auth-walled and the platform provides no API per the PMC paper *Optimizing the HMIS in Uttar Pradesh* (2022). It's at best a **liveness signal** in the Trust Scorer ("does this facility report HMIS data?"). The ABDM HFR, by contrast, has a near-1:1 schema overlap with the Virtue Foundation columns: facility name, 12-digit unique ID, ownership, system of medicine, facility type/sub-type, services/specialization, IPD bed counts (general/private/ICU-with-ventilator/NICU), full address with PIN and lat/lon, linked HPR doctors, and PMJAY/NHRR cross-IDs. Production ABDM API access requires CERT-IN audited "Safe-to-Host" certification and is infeasible in 72 hours, but the **sandbox at sandbox.abdm.gov.in is free with mobile-OTP signup** and exposes OAuth2 client-credentials flow for the search endpoint. Browser-automated calls to `facility.abdm.gov.in/searchV2` via Playwright at ~0.5 req/s complete 10K name lookups in roughly six hours.

**The de-risking move is to pre-load the data.gov.in NHP Hospital Directory** (CSV under GODL-India open license, ~3,000 geocoded records from the National Health Portal) as a deterministic first-pass matcher. Index it in SQLite, fuzzy-match by (PIN, name) using RapidFuzz, and treat HFR calls as enrichment, not critical path. The Trust Scorer then weights matches: HFR exact = 1.0, HFR fuzzy = 0.7, NHP-only = 0.5, HMIS-reporting flag = +0.1, no-match = 0.0.

**The narrative this combination unlocks is unbeatable for a World Bank summit:** *"We validate civil-society NGO data against India's flagship Ayushman Bharat Digital Mission registry — the same registry the Government of India is building toward Universal Health Coverage. The Trust Scorer becomes a bridge that lets civil-society datasets earn ABDM-grade trust without waiting for full ABDM onboarding."* Tertiary enrichment worth name-checking: OpenStreetMap/Healthsites.io (Overpass `amenity=hospital`, ODbL-licensed), NFHS-5 district factsheets (district-context features), the All-India Pincode Directory on data.gov.in for canonical PIN→district resolution, and Rural Health Statistics 2022-23 PDFs for denominators.

## 5. IPHS 2022 + WHO SARA: 42 rules, ship 15

IPHS 2022 was released by MoHFW on 16 April 2022 in **four volumes**: SDH/DH (Vol I, 244pp), CHC/UCHC (Vol II, 176pp), HWC-PHC/UPHC/Polyclinic (Vol III, 128pp), and HWC-SHC/UHWC (Vol IV, 120pp), all hosted at `nhm.gov.in/images/pdf/guidelines/iphs/iphs-revised-guidlines-2022/` with mirrors at `nhsrcindia.org/IPHS2022` and the compliance ODK portal `iphs.mohfw.gov.in` (≥80% score = "IPHS-compliant"). Every requirement carries an **Essential vs Desirable** flag — the most important axis for your validator, since only Essential gaps should produce HIGH-severity flags.

The structural skeleton matters because the same Pydantic schema needs to enforce different rules per tier. **SHC-HWC** serves 5,000 (plain) or 3,000 (hilly/tribal/desert), has 2 day-care beds essential, no IPD or surgery, staffed by a CHO + ANM + male MPW. **PHC** serves 30,000 (plain) or 20,000 (hilly), 6 beds essential (10 for 24×7), 2 MOs + 1 AYUSH MO + 3–4 nurses (≥4 at 24×7), no caesarean, no major surgery, no ICU, no blood bank, no X-ray, no USG. **CHC** has two flavors that determine almost every other rule: **non-FRU (30 beds, no surgery/caesarean/blood storage)** vs. **FRU CHC (30/50/100 beds, must have functional OT, Blood Storage Unit, and the five essential specialists: Surgeon, Physician, Obstetrician-Gynaecologist, Paediatrician, and Anaesthesiologist or LSAS-trained MO)**. **SDH/DH** serves 1 bed/1,000 essential, with 12 essential specialist cadres, ICU at 1:1 nurse ratio, HDU at 1:2, SNCU/MNCU at 12 beds each in 100-bed configs, CT essential at DH, and the full equipment annexure including ventilators (≥1 per ICU bed), defibrillators, multipara monitors, and blood bank refrigeration with component separator at DH level.

The research surfaces **42 machine-readable rules**; the right hackathon move is to ship the highest-impact 15 covering ~80% of realistic contradictions, then add the rest as time allows. The starter set: surgery without anaesthesia provider (R01), surgery without functional OT (R02), caesarean without BSU (R03), CEmONC without obstetrician (R04), ICU without ventilator (R05), delivery without radiant warmer (R09), USG without radiologist or PCPNDT-trained MO (R13), PHC claiming caesarean/ICU/blood-bank (R20), FRU CHC missing one of five specialists (R22), DH missing CT/ICU/blood-bank/SNCU (R26), no power back-up (R30), emergency without ambulance link (R33), delivery without oxytocin (R37), immunization without cold chain (R39), TB without sputum diagnostic (R41).

The recommended rulebook format is YAML with `id`, `severity`, `framework` (IPHS volume citation or SARA tracer name), `applies_to` (tier set), `when` (predicate), `flag` (human-readable contradiction), and `remediation`. Load into a `validator_rules` Delta table keyed on `id` for join-based evaluation at scale. Two implementation tips that matter: **synonym-map staff roles** (DGO, MS, MBBS+DA, LSAS-MO all need canonical resolution before predicate evaluation) and **disambiguate tier from the data** rather than trusting labels — beds + OT + anaesthesiologist + blood-storage forms a deterministic decision tree that's more reliable than the `facility_type` column.

WHO SARA (Reference Manual v2.2) provides the international cross-reference. SARA measures three domains: Service Availability (densities), General Service Readiness (basic amenities, basic equipment, standard precautions, diagnostic capacity, **25 tracer essential medicines**), and Service-Specific Readiness across 17 programs including the three "bellwether" surgical procedures (laparotomy, open-fracture management, caesarean section). Where IPHS prescribes, SARA measures — pair them so HIGH-severity rules cite IPHS clauses while readiness scores cite SARA tracer items. This dual citation is what makes the Validator Agent feel rigorous in the demo.

## 6. Cursor 3.x: subagents, skills, and a $100 budget that goes far

Cursor shipped a meaningful platform shift in early 2026. **Cursor 2.4 (Jan 22, 2026)** introduced Subagents and the open Agent Skills standard (SKILL.md, auto-discovered from `.cursor/skills/`, `.claude/skills/`, and `.codex/skills/`). **Cursor 3.0 (Apr 2026)** brought the Agents Window for parallel local/worktree/cloud/remote-SSH agents and **multi-root workspaces** that let one agent session span the frontend and backend simultaneously — exactly the topology of your Lovable + Vercel + Databricks stack. **Cursor 3.1 (Apr 13, 2026)** added tiled layout, interactive canvases, and the slash commands `/debug`, `/btw`, `/config`, `/statusline`. MCP servers now live in `.cursor/mcp.json` and load lazily, cutting agent token use 46.9% per the Jan 7 update.

**The $100 Cursor credit math:** Cursor Pro+ at $60/month gives a $60 model-credit pool, equivalent to ~225 Sonnet 4.6 requests OR ~45 Opus 4.7 requests OR effectively unlimited Auto/Composer. **Strategy: Auto mode default, Sonnet 4.6 for typical work, Opus 4.7 only for hard debugging or architecture review, never Max Mode.** Set the spending cap to $100 immediately in Settings → Account.

The **Karpathy skills repo (`forrestchang/andrej-karpathy-skills`, 86.9k stars)** is much smaller than its reputation suggests — it's a single CLAUDE.md plus one `karpathy-guidelines/SKILL.md` plus a `.cursor/rules/karpathy-guidelines.mdc`. The four principles it enforces — don't assume / surface confusion, surgical changes / minimum code, goal-driven execution, push back when warranted — are directly aimed at the #1 hackathon failure mode of agents silently overcomplicating extraction pipelines. **Drop CLAUDE.md and the .mdc into your repo at hour zero.** It biases toward caution over speed; for trivial scaffolding let the agent execute, but for the agentic core orchestrator code this is precisely the bias you want.

Recommended `.cursor/mcp.json` for this build: **Databricks managed MCP** (Public Preview, Apr 2, 2026 — three flavors covering UC functions, Vector Search, and Genie via `uc-mcp-proxy`), **Firecrawl MCP** (web scraping with JS rendering, free tier 10/min for healthcare guidelines), **Qdrant MCP** in local-mode (no infra, useful for local IPHS-document RAG before you wire UC Vector Search), **Context7 MCP** (live framework docs to eliminate hallucinated Databricks SDK calls), and **Playwright MCP** for browser-driven scripted demos or HFR scraping. There is no mature healthcare-specific or geospatial MCP as of April 2026 and no native ragas/promptfoo MCP — wire evaluation as an MLflow-instrumented notebook instead.

The recommended repo layout: `AGENTS.md` and `CLAUDE.md` at the root, `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` for `python-style`, `databricks-conventions`, and `healthcare-safety` (PHI handling, never log raw patient text), `.cursor/skills/` for procedural how-tos like `deploy-databricks/SKILL.md` and `extract-clinical-doc/SKILL.md`, `.cursor/plans/` for `architecture.md` and `demo-script.md`, and `.cursor/hooks/` for stop hooks that fire on test pass to close self-correcting loops. Use **Background Agents** (Ctrl+E or `&` prefix) for parallel iteration: implementation agent on `feature/extraction-pipeline`, test-writing agent on `feature/eval-suite`, plan-mode agent drafting the demo script. Add a `.cursor/Dockerfile` with cached system deps to avoid 5 minutes of `apt install` on each cold start, and remember background agents always bill usage-based regardless of subscription credits.

## 7. Lovable → Vercel → Databricks: the only architecture that works in 72 hours

Lovable generates **React + Vite + TypeScript + Tailwind + shadcn/ui + Radix** — not Next.js. It has a first-party **Databricks Connector** (announced March 2026) that uses OAuth M2M with a service principal plus a SQL Warehouse, but **Free Edition has no SQL Warehouse**, so the connector is unusable for this hackathon. The viable architecture is therefore **FastAPI on Vercel as the proxy, Databricks Model Serving as the agent backend, Lovable as the React client**.

**Do not put FastAPI on Databricks Apps.** Databricks Apps require Premium-tier workspace, which Free Edition is not. Every "FastAPI on Databricks Apps" cookbook you'll find on apps-cookbook.dev is post-hackathon material. The Vercel Python runtime auto-detects FastAPI from `requirements.txt`, looks for an `app` object in `app.py`/`index.py`/`api/index.py`, and supports streaming responses for chat UIs. The bundle is capped at 250MB unzipped — use `excludeFiles` in `vercel.json` to drop tests, notebooks, and `__pycache__`, and pin minimal deps (`databricks-sdk`, not `databricks-connect`).

**The CORS configuration that actually works** uses `allow_origin_regex=r"https://.*\.lovable\.app"` because Lovable preview URLs change per build, plus an explicit OPTIONS handler — preflight failures on first call but success on retry is a signature symptom of a missing OPTIONS path. Put the Databricks PAT in Vercel env vars without the `VITE_` prefix (the prefix exposes vars to the browser; only short-lived demo bearer tokens should be `VITE_*`). A simple bearer-token check on the Vercel function is sufficient auth for a hackathon — skip OAuth, skip cookies (the public-suffix-list registration of `*.lovable.app` and `*.vercel.app` makes cross-domain cookies break anyway).

For the Vercel function timeout, extend to 60s in `vercel.json` `functions.maxDuration` and stream incrementally — Databricks Model Serving has a hard **297-second cap** and Vercel Hobby's default 10s will surface as truncated responses long before that. **Disable scale-to-zero on the Model Serving endpoint at least one hour before demo** or send a warmup ping every 25 minutes, otherwise judges get a 10–20 second cold-start dead-air moment that kills the room.

## 8. Demo craft: how to make a 60-second video judges remember

Devpost judge interviews (Square, Databricks, Google, Atlassian, NEAR) are unanimous: **judges decide in under 30 seconds**. If your demo doesn't run or doesn't make sense in that window, they move on. The canonical winning structure for a 60–90 second tech video is a 5–10 second human-face hook with one specific question (an ASHA worker in Rajasthan asks in Hindi: *"नज़दीकी सरकारी अस्पताल में 24×7 anaesthesiologist है क्या?"*), 10–20 seconds naming the problem with a body-count or rupee-cost, then the golden-path demo with the trace visible, then a 10-second close that quantifies replacement and name-checks the sponsor stack.

**Visualizing chain-of-thought in 60 seconds** has six tactics that consistently work: **split-screen the MLflow Trace UI alongside the chat output** (the trace tree is already designed for this — show parent-child spans with RETRIEVER, TOOL, LLM types updating in real time); **lower-third labels** synced to the action ("RETRIEVING IPHS-CHC-Annexure-6… CHECKING anaesthesiologist… DRAFTING contradiction note"); **show the agent disagreeing with itself or asking for confirmation** on a clinically risky case (this directly addresses safety-rubric points); **show the citation** ("Agent retrieved this from IPHS Vol II §8.3.1"); **pre-test two "wow" Genie or agent questions verbatim**; and **show one real downstream action**, not just chat — book the appointment, dispatch the SMS, fill the ABDM HFR enrichment form. The Out-of-Pocket "U good?" demo is the canonical case study: the audacity of the agent autonomously navigating a phone IVR is what made it memorable, not the reasoning quality.

Storytelling for the social-impact rubric requires three moves drawn from MIT Hacking Medicine, UC Berkeley's Rural Health Hackathon, and the NYU 2026 Healthcare Access winners. **Lead with one named persona** ("Lakshmi, 32, gestational diabetes, 60 km from nearest endocrinologist") rather than "1.4 billion lives." **Frame the agent as augmenting the ASHA worker, not replacing them** — Berkeley SPH's CIO is explicit that judges in social-impact tracks reward asset-based framings over deficit-based ones. **End with a specific, fundable next 90 days** — "with $X we will pilot in Banswara district with Virtue Foundation" — and an explicit failure-modes slide naming what the agent does NOT do (no diagnosis, human-in-the-loop for surgical decisions). Cornell's AI Hackathon brief is unusually direct: *"Strong submissions clarify failure modes, tradeoffs, or limits rather than claim complete safety."*

The recorded video matters more than the live demo — pre-record by hour 18 as a backup against rate limits, cold starts, and venue Wi-Fi drops. Use Remotion + Edge TTS + ffmpeg if you want the synthetic-voiceover path Tamir Dresher documented for Microsoft Hackathon 2026.

## 9. Five creative angles that elevate the build, ranked

**The Conformal-Calibrated TrustScore is the headline contribution.** Combine self-consistency confidence + cross-source agreement (Databricks embedding-distance approach from their Virtue Foundation blog) + IPHS rule-compliance score + SelfCheckGPT-NLI contradiction penalty into a single logistic, **calibrated via isotonic regression on a 200-record human-labeled gold set, then wrapped in split conformal prediction** for finite-sample 90% coverage guarantees. Render per-field Green/Yellow/Red badges with hoverable cards showing each component, the contradicting evidence span, and the violated IPHS clause. This is the single most defensible deliverable for the Discovery & Verification 35% pillar and answers the challenge's "statistical prediction intervals" line item directly. Cost: 8–10 hours.

**The Medical-Desert Heatmap is the social-impact pillar in one screen.** Compute district-level population/facility ratios against IPHS norms (1 SHC per 5,000 plain, 1 PHC per 30,000, 1 CHC per 120,000), specialty-distance proxies via haversine to nearest specialty-offering facility, 60-minute drive-time isochrones via OSRM/OpenRouteService, and a Composite Coverage Gap Index following the BMC Public Health 2020 methodology with bivariate LISA. Published Indian medical-desert literature consistently identifies tribal Rajasthan (Barmer, Banswara, Dungarpur), Bihar, Jharkhand, the KBK belt of Odisha, MP tribal districts (Alirajpur, Jhabua), and Northeast hill districts as worst-served — your map should agree with the literature, lending instant credibility. Render with kepler.gl or pydeck. **This is also the angle that maps directly onto Virtue Foundation's own flagship Actionable Data Initiative**, so you literally extend the partner's mission. Cost: 6–8 hours.

**The WhatsApp-style ASHA Chat Demo is the wow moment in the video.** Three or four hand-picked queries: *"नज़दीकी सरकारी अस्पताल में gynecologist 24x7 है क्या?"*, *"Show me PHCs in Banswara claiming 24×7 OPD but with no MO posted"*, *"Find the nearest FRU CHC with anaesthetist and BSU within 50 km that accepts PMJAY."* Real prior art to cite: **ASHABot** (Ramjee et al., arXiv:2409.10913 — a deployed WhatsApp + GPT-4 chatbot for ASHAs in Rajasthan), **ARTPark @ IISc's LLM Assistant for Frontline Health Workers**, and Microsoft Research Bangalore's **CataractBot** for patients. Build with React chat → PydanticAI agent → tools for `geospatial_search`, `query_facility`, `compare_claim_vs_iphs`. Voice-to-text via Whisper is appealing but risky live (cold start, mic permissions) — leave it as a stretch demo. Cost: 5–7 hours.

**The Multi-Persona Validator Debate exploits the IDP-Innovation 30% rubric.** Three personas — Skeptical Auditor, IPHS Inspector, Local Doctor — debate each contradiction using Self-Contrast (Zhang et al., ACL 2024, addresses Reflexion's echo-chamber problem) and **expose the transcript** in the UI. The MAR paper (arXiv:2512.20845) shows multi-persona Reflexion materially improves over single-agent self-critique. Cost: 6–8 hours.

**Multi-modal certificate verification with Mistral OCR 3** (released Dec 2025, $2/1k pages, 88.9% on handwriting vs Azure 78.2%, 96.6% on tables vs Textract 84.8%) is the stretch goal that lets you say "we ingest scanned licenses and registration certificates against the same Pydantic schema." Cost: 4–5 hours, only if extraction core is solid by Saturday evening.

Background reading worth name-checking in the slides: MedAgentBench (Stanford/NEJM AI 2025), AgentClinic (ICLR 2025), MedAgentsBench (NeurIPS 2025), Biomni (Stanford bioRxiv 2025), and the npj Digital Medicine 2026 benchmark showing Manus/OpenManus achieving only modest gains on AgentClinic — meaning *simple, well-validated agent loops still win*, which is good news for a 72-hour build.

## 10. The ten time traps ranked by severity

The risks compound nonlinearly — a single architectural mistake at hour 6 cascades into a frantic 4 AM rebuild. The four cliffs from the BLUF reappear here as risks 1–4, and the rest are second-tier but still sharp.

**Tier 1 (architecture-defining).** *Free Edition outbound-internet allowlist* will be discovered at hour 14 when the agent can't call the HFR — mitigation is to do all external tool calls from the Vercel layer, not from Databricks notebooks. *Databricks Apps require Premium tier* invalidates any architecture copy-pasted from apps-cookbook.dev — mitigation is FastAPI-on-Vercel from hour zero. *Model Serving cold start plus 297-second timeout* will hit during the live demo — mitigation is to disable scale-to-zero an hour before, send warmup pings, and pre-record a 60-second backup video. *CORS between `*.lovable.app` and Vercel* costs two hours per occurrence — mitigation is `allow_origin_regex` plus an explicit OPTIONS handler on hour zero.

**Tier 2 (operational).** *Free Edition daily quota exhaustion mid-Saturday afternoon* (reset is next day, sometimes next month) — cap eval runs aggressively and mock LLM calls during pipeline development. *VPN from Pakistan plus email-OTP signup flakiness* — register from a stable network with Google sign-in before VPN. *Vercel 250MB function-bundle limit* surfaces only on first deploy — pin minimal deps and use `excludeFiles`. *Cursor Pro+ Opus-4.7-default credit burn* (~45 requests per $60) — Auto mode default, $100 hard cap.

**Tier 3 (process discipline).** *Premature multi-agent orchestration* before a single agent + eval works — enforce the Karpathy CLAUDE.md principles. *Background-agent setup overhead* on every cold VM — ship a `.cursor/Dockerfile`.

The features that look great in screenshots but eat too much time deserve their own line: **avoid** custom RAG chunking optimization beyond two hours (diminishing returns), building custom MCP servers (use existing), heavy Higgsfield motion animations on the hero (5–8s page-load tax that judges notice), live voice input (STT cold-start failures), real OAuth flows (bearer token plus a `?demo=1` short-circuit is enough), and Genie integration without a SQL Warehouse (Free Edition doesn't have one). **Do invest** in: a one-page architecture diagram, a 90-second crisp demo script, the fallback recorded video, an MLflow evaluation table screenshot, and a judge-friendly Streamlit/Gradio dashboard for the eval story.

## What to do at hour zero

The scaffolding sequence is short and ordered. **Repo:** drop `CLAUDE.md` (Karpathy) and `AGENTS.md` and `.cursor/rules/{python-style,databricks-conventions,healthcare-safety}.mdc` at the root. **Cursor:** configure `.cursor/mcp.json` with Databricks managed MCP, Firecrawl, Qdrant, Context7, Playwright; set spending cap to $100; default to Auto mode. **Databricks:** register Free Edition from a non-VPN network with Google sign-in; pick us-east-2 or us-west-2; create catalog `hackathon` with schemas `bronze`/`silver`/`gold`/`ai`; create managed volume; upload the VF Excel; load to a Delta table with Change Data Feed enabled; add `COMMENT ON COLUMN` annotations. **Vercel:** `vc init fastapi`; deploy a hello-world; configure `allow_origin_regex` and OPTIONS handler. **Lovable:** scaffold UI; set `VITE_API_BASE_URL` to the Vercel URL. **Data:** download data.gov.in NHP Hospital Directory CSV, index in SQLite. **Eval:** freeze a 30–200 example human-labeled gold set by hour 4. **Backup:** pre-record a 60-second demo video by hour 18.

